1️⃣ Parent vs Owning Side (Core Difference)
Concept	Meaning	Who decides it
Parent / Child	Logical domain relationship	Business model
Owning Side / Inverse Side	Who manages the foreign key in DB	JPA mapping
So:
✔ Parent/Child → conceptual
✔ Owning/Inverse → technical (JPA)
________________________________________
2️⃣ Example (Department–Employee)
Department 1 -------- * Employee
Logical Relationship
Parent → Department
Child → Employee
Because a department contains employees.
________________________________________
JPA Ownership
Employee → Owning Side
Department → Inverse Side
Because:
@ManyToOne
@JoinColumn(name="department_id")
controls the foreign key.
________________________________________
3️⃣ So Here
Entity	Role
Department	Parent + Inverse
Employee	Child + Owning
So yes ✅ Parent is not always owning side.
________________________________________
4️⃣ Is It Situational?
Yes 👍 ownership depends on where @JoinColumn is placed.
Example:
Case 1 (Most Common)
@ManyToOne
@JoinColumn(name="department_id")
Owning side → Employee
________________________________________
Case 2 (Unidirectional OneToMany)
@OneToMany
@JoinColumn(name="department_id")
Now:
Owning side → Department
Even though Department is parent.
________________________________________
5️⃣ Another Example (OneToOne)
Example: User ↔ Profile
You could design:
Case A
User
@OneToOne
@JoinColumn
User = owning side
________________________________________
Case B
Profile
@OneToOne
@JoinColumn
Profile = owning side
So owning side is decided by mapping, not by domain.
________________________________________
6️⃣ Golden Rule
Ownership is determined by:
@JoinColumn
or
mappedBy
Rule:
Annotation	Meaning
@JoinColumn	Owning side
mappedBy	Inverse side
________________________________________
7️⃣ Important Interview Statement
Best explanation:
Parent/Child is a logical domain relationship, while Owning/Inverse side is a JPA persistence concept that determines which entity manages the foreign key in the database.
________________________________________
8️⃣ Visual Summary
LOGICAL MODEL
-----------------
Department (Parent)
      |
      | 1..*
      |
Employee (Child)


JPA MAPPING
-----------------
Department (@OneToMany mappedBy) → Inverse
Employee (@ManyToOne JoinColumn) → Owning
________________________________________
9️⃣ Final Answer to Your Question
✔ Yes Parent and Owning Side are different concepts
✔ Parent is not necessarily the owning side
✔ Ownership is decided by JPA mapping (@JoinColumn)
✔ So it is situational
Your understanding is correct.
